#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:1
msgid "Improvements related to vtk Polyhedral cell storage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:3
msgid "Storing faces as vtkCellArray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:5
msgid ""
"When storing face information for polyhedral cells, `vtkUnstructuredGrid` "
"uses a `vtkIdTypeArray` in a special format that looks awfully similar to "
"how `vtkCellArray` used maintain its internal storage. The new internal "
"storage simply changes it to using `vtkCellArray` instead. That will allow "
"us to use a non-interleaved storage for faces. Together with using a "
"`vtkCellArray` for `FaceLocations`  the one-2-many relationship can be "
"easily preserved without resorting to custom layout used by the `Faces` "
"array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:9
msgid "So here's the current storage structure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:10
msgid ""
"**Connectivity** (`vtkCellArray`): simply stores point ids for all points "
"for each polyhedral element"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:11
msgid ""
"**Faces** (`vtkCellArray`): each element defines a polygonal face. The "
"indices per element directly refer to point ids."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:12
msgid ""
"**FaceLocations** (`vtkCellArray`): each element identifies a polyhedral "
"cell. The indices per element reference face defined in the **ElementFace** "
"array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:15
msgid "Contrast this with how this information was previously stored:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:16
msgid ""
"**Connectivity** (`vtkCellArray`): simply stores point ids for all points "
"for each polyhedral element (same as in the new proposal)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:17
msgid ""
"**(Legacy)Faces** (`vtkIdTypeArray`): an interleaved array of the form "
"`(numCellFaces, numFace0Pts, id1, id2, id3, numFace1Pts,id1, id2, id3, ...)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:18
msgid ""
"**(Legacy)FaceLocations** (`vtkIdTypeArray`): offset array into "
"**(Legacy)Faces** array indicating where the faces for a corresponding cell "
"are stored"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:21
msgid "Backward compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:23
msgid ""
"To ensure a nice transition to the new storage, some old API are kept. More "
"precisely the method `void SetCells(vtkUnsignedCharArray* cellTypes, "
"vtkCellArray* cells, vtkIdTypeArray* faceLocations, vtkIdTypeArray* faces);` "
"from vtkUnstructuredGrid is deprecated but can still be used. In this case a "
"copy of faceLocations and faces data will be done. Another case are the "
"`GetFaces` and  `GetFaceLocations` methods. They are still available  but an "
"internal cache with the old internal layout is used. It means that they "
"should be considered as read only methods and not be relied on to change "
"internal data of vtkUnstructuredGrid. The caching process may impact a bit "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:29
msgid ""
"The `FaceConn` and `FaceLocs` internal arrays of "
"`vtkUnstructuredGridCellIterator` are no longer available as "
"`vtkIdTypeArray`. This may break your subclasses if you rely on them "
"directly and not on the exposed API of `vtkUnstructuredGridCellIterator`. A "
"solution to keep using them in subclasses is to define them directly in "
"subclasses and handle their logic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:32
msgid "Compatibility with Conduit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/vtk-polyhedral-cells-storage.md:34
msgid ""
"The new layout is much closer to how Conduit store its polyhedral cell "
"information. Thus, some gain should be expected on the long run."
msgstr ""
